{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632814"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:44:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:44:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17442"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17442"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10132"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70843"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10132"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56310"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5452"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23815"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70843"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIn epidemiological studies, various measures are used to quantify the association between exposures and outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the calculation of relative risk?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Odds in exposed divided by odds in unexposed","Number of exposed cases divided by total exposed","Risk difference between exposed and unexposed","Proportion of cases that were exposed","Incidence in exposed divided by incidence in unexposed"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eincidence in exposed divided by incidence in unexposed\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the calculation of relative risk. This measure compares the probability of an outcome occurring in an exposed group to the probability in an unexposed group.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eodds in exposed divided by odds in unexposed\u003C/strong\u003E describes the odds ratio, which is a different measure commonly used in case-control studies.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enumber of exposed cases divided by total exposed\u003C/strong\u003E only calculates the incidence rate in the exposed group, which is just one component of the relative risk calculation.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erisk difference between exposed and unexposed\u003C/strong\u003E represents the attributable risk, which is an absolute measure calculated through subtraction rather than division.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproportion of cases that were exposed\u003C/strong\u003E represents the exposure rate among cases, which is used to calculate other epidemiological measures but not relative risk.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EA relative risk of 1.0 indicates no association between exposure and outcome. Values greater than 1.0 suggest the exposure increases risk, while values less than 1.0 suggest the exposure decreases risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Relative risk compares the probability of an outcome between exposed and unexposed groups.","Relative risk is calculated by dividing the incidence in the exposed group by the incidence in the unexposed group.","A relative risk greater than 1 indicates increased risk in the exposed group, while less than 1 indicates decreased risk."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021.","Ray, Sumantra, and others (eds), Oxford Handbook of Clinical and Healthcare Research, 1, Oxford Medical Handbooks (Oxford, 2016; online edn, Oxford Academic, 1 Mar. 2016), https://doi.org/10.1093/med/9780199608478.001.0001","Peacock, Janet L., and Phil J. Peacock, Oxford Handbook of Medical Statistics 2e, 2 edn, Oxford Medical Handbooks (Oxford, 2020; online edn, Oxford Academic, 1 Mar. 2020), https://doi.org/10.1093/med/9780198743583.001.0001"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56310"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17442"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56310"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:33:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:33:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10132"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70843"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description"